The doctrine of atonis, as being the original elements of all things. is silly and untenable: but even granting it to be true, and so supposing the gods to have arisen from atoms‚ their immortality would be in contradiction with it (65-68). ButA in order to be able to maintain this immortality Epicurus takes his usual course when he wishes to escape the consequences os his own principles 3 he flies to other arbitrary and inconceivable propositions. 'l'he gods, says he, are not corporeal, but only quasi corporeal beings.¹ But this quasi corporealily is a word devoid of sense, con· veying no idea even to Epicurus and his disciples (69-75). But let this pass, if we will. the case is no better sor the assertion that the gods have human forms. The reasons given by the Epicureans in support of this are next resuted one after another; and especially the assertion, that no person can imagine the gods under any other form, is rejected as practically false, since many represent them under the figures of beasts (76-82). But it is quite unworthy of a philosopher to appeal to representations of that sort. A person might with equal justice also maintain that the gods really bear the names that are traditionally used to denote them3 and the foolish- ness of this is directly apparent, when we observe that the same gods are differently called among different nations.'²
